'''Air pollution forecasting''' is the application of science and technology to predict the composition of the [[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]] for a given location and time.

The forecast may give the pollutants concentration or the [[air quality index]].

Countries and cities are given forecasts by organizations like the [[EPA]], as well as private companies like AirVisual, Aerostate, BreezoMeter and PlumeLabs that give air pollution forecast.

==Techniques==
* Air pollution forecasting can be done by coupling [[weather forecasting]] systems with [[Chemical transport model]].
* Using [[machine learning]] techniques<ref>[http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S135223100000385X "Neural networks and periodic components used in air quality forecasting"]</ref>. 

The forecast takes into account local emission sources (like nearby [[traffic]] or industry) and remote sources (e.g. [[dust]] that is carried by [[Air parcel|air parcels]] and follows the [[wind]] direction).

==Motivation==
* By knowing the air quality forecast one can decide how to act, e.g. due to air pollution [[Air_pollution#Health_effects|health effects]], one can choose the best time to do an outdoor activity.
* Deciding whether to put on a skin care ointment<ref>{{cite web |title=Dermalogica & BreezoMeter partner to educate on pollution's skin effects |url=https://blog.breezometer.com/dermalogica-cosmetics |accessdate=31 May 2018}}</ref>.
* Find the cleanest route for cars<ref>{{cite web |title=Clean Air Route Finder |url=https://www.london.gov.uk/what-we-do/environment/pollution-and-air-quality/clean-air-route-finder |publisher=Greater London Authority}}</ref>.
* Deciding whether to leave the windows open or closed<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Pollution Maps: Users Love Them, Your Brand Needs Them |url=https://blog.breezometer.com/air-pollution-maps}}</ref>.

