In [[Greek mythology]], '''Astris''' (or '''[[Asteria (mythology)|Asteria]]''')<ref> Parada, p. 30.</ref> was, in [[Nonnus]]'s ''[[Dionysiaca]]'',<ref>[[Nonnus]]. ''[[Dionysiaca]], Book 17.282, 23.236, 26.355, 27.199&#x2013;203, 33.151&#x2013;152.'' Rouse, pp. 52, 53, n. ''c'' says the name Astris is a Nonnus invention.</ref> one of the [[Heliades]], daughters of [[Helios]], either by the [[Oceanid]] [[Clymene (mythology)|Clymene]]<ref>Nonnus. ''Dionysiaca, Book 17.282.''</ref> or the [[Oceanid]] [[Ceto (Oceanid)|Ceto]].<ref>Nonnus. ''Dionysiaca, Book 26.351&#x2013;355.''</ref> She married the river god [[Hydaspes (mythology)|Hydaspes]] (the modern [[Jhelum River]]) and became mother of [[Deriades]], king in [[India]].
